# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synchronous-ethernet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It has become dominant in enterprise networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This dominance has led to high production-volume components, which in turn have allowed extremely low cost per bit.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Likewise, Ethernet has a long history of re-inventing itself.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] From the original copper coaxial cable format ("thicknet") it has extended its scope to nearly all copper, optical fiber and wireless physical media.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Bit rates have continued to increase, traditionally growing tenfold each time a new rate is defined.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Gigabit Ethernet interfaces are widely deployed in PCs and servers, and 10 Gbit/s in local area network (LAN) backbones.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Rates up to 100 Gigabit Ethernet were standardized in 2010 and 2011.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet's dominance is partly attributed to the simple advantages for the industry of adopting a single standard to drive up volumes and drive down prices.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] In part, it is also due to ease of deployment, using its ability to self-configure based on the key concepts of *learning bridge* (flooding, and associating learned destination addresses with bridge ports) and Spanning Tree Protocol (the protocol used for avoiding bridging loops).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Historically, competing protocols and cabling have been created in order to access higher speed devices than contemporary Ethernet-connected devices handled at an affordable price.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Examples include FireWire and Light Peak.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] One motive to create competing standards has been to drive down the price of comparable-speed Ethernet devices.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Once this purpose is achieved, competing standards tend to disappear or be confined to very specialized niches.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet is a fairly simple protocol which has scaled to hundreds of thousands of times faster speeds and consistently been able to adapt to meet the needs and demands of new markets.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] For example, time domain capabilities are being added to IEEE 802.3 Ethernet to support IEEE 802.1 Audio Video Bridging (AVB), and these capabilities will be applicable to time sensitive carrier applications likewise IEEE 1588.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Customer LAN networks are increasingly connected to wide-area telecommunications networks over Ethernet interfaces or to devices that bridge digital subscriber line (DSL) or wireless to these.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Moreover, customers are familiar with the capabilities of Ethernet networks, and would like to extend these capabilities to multi-site networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Meanwhile, the needs of such networks have expanded to include many services previously handled only on the LAN or by specialized connections, notably video and backup.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It is not practical to expand most small networks beyond 1G or at most 2G (dual teaming gigabit) capacity per segment, since the bottleneck remains in the wide area links to other offices and online services.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] They are also constrained as services cannot be migrated from local to wide area services too fast lest they exceed the total provisioning available and result in unacceptable quality.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Services that try to expand too fast lose money while those that wait too long lose customers.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Accordingly, carriers must expand their services conservatively and pay close attention to quality of service (QoS).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The MEF was formed in 2001 in order to develop ubiquitous business services for Enterprise users principally accessed over optical metropolitan networks in order to connect their Enterprise LANs.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The principal concept was to bring the simplicity and cost model of Ethernet to the wide area network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] To create a market in Ethernet services, it is necessary to clarify and standardise the services to be provided.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Recognising this, the industry created the MEF.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] All these services provide standard definitions of such characteristics as bandwidth, resilience and service multiplexing, allowing customers to compare service offerings and facilitating service level agreements (SLAs).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The services are categorized as an E-line service type, with an expectation of low frame delay, frame delay variation and frame loss ratio.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] EPL is implemented using a point-to-point EVC with no service multiplexing at each UNI (physical interface), i.e., all service frames at the UNI are mapped to a single EVC (a.k.a. all-to-one bundling).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Due to a high degree of transparency, EPL is often used to provide point-to-point transparent LAN service (TLS), where the service frame's header and payload are identical at both the source and destination UNI.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Some implementations tunnel most Ethernet Layer 2 control protocols (L2CPs) except for some link-layer L2CPs such as IEEE 802.3x pause frames.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Unlike EPL, EVPL allows for service multiplexing, i.e., multiple EVCs or Ethernet services per UNI.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The other difference between the EVPL and EPL is the degree of transparency: while EPL is highly transparent, filtering only the pause frames, EVPL is required to either peer or drop most of the Layer 2 control protocols.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The MEF does not specify how Ethernet services are to be provided in a carrier network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Despite the advantages described above, Ethernet has traditionally had a number of limitations in the WAN application.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The "bridge" and "spanning tree" concepts described above do not scale to large international networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Moreover, Ethernet has lacked some of the dependability features necessary in this application (in particular, mechanisms to isolate one customer's traffic from another, to measure performance of a customer service instance, and to rapidly detect and repair failures in large networks).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Because of these limitations, and because of the need to make use of pre-existing equipment, Ethernet services have been carried across wide area networks using other technologies.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Two types of technology have been widely used, while a third (Carrier-Ethernet transport) is rapidly emerging as a viable and logical option for Carrier-Ethernet services.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet services are carried over IP/MPLS networks making use of a wide range of IP-related protocols.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet links are transported as "pseudowires" using MPLS label-switched paths (LSPs) inside an outer MPLS "tunnel".
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This strategy can support both point-to-point (Virtual Private Wire Service - VPWS) and multipoint (Virtual Private LAN service - VPLS) services, and has recently achieved significant deployment in routed networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It makes use of a number of basic transport protocols, including SDH and (increasingly) Ethernet.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Proponents of Carrier-Class Ethernet argue Ethernet is the best for Metro Area Networks because all data traffic originates as Ethernet.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet's ubiquitous presence in the LANs worldwide drives down the cost of Ethernet as a technology.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Thus, the use of Ethernet in a metro network allows service providers to take advantage of volumes that a much larger enterprise segment commands.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier-Ethernet Transport (CET) usually involves an evolution of conventional Ethernet and comprises multiple technology components.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Provider Backbone Bridges (PBB) provides the scalability and a secure demarcation, while Provider Backbone Bridge Traffic Engineering (PBB-TE, commonly called PBT) provides for traffic-engineering and an effective transport for protected Ethernet services.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Connectivity-Fault Management (CFM-OAM) provides the much-required OAM that makes Ethernet carrier grade.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier Ethernet demarcation is a key element in Carrier Ethernet services and transport networks for business, wholesale and mobile backhaul applications, as it enables service providers to extend their control over the entire service path, starting from the hand off points.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This is achieved by connecting customer premises equipment (CPE) to the network with provider-owned demarcation devices that are deployed at customer locations, thereby enabling a clear separation between the user and provider networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier Ethernet demarcation devices (EDD) are required to support services, such as Ethernet Private Line (EPL), Ethernet Virtual Private Line (EVPL or E-LAN), and Ethernet Virtual Private Tree (E-Tree), as specified by the MEF.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Such support needs to include service level agreement (SLA) management capabilities, with consistent performance over fiber, DSL, bonded PDH, and SDH/SONET access lines.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The industry has made a concerted effort to resolve the limitations of Ethernet in the WAN described above, so as to allow the use of "native" Ethernet technologies by network providers.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The key roles have been played by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) 802.1 and 802.3 standards committees.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] IEEE 802.1 has addressed the scalability and management issues in the standards for Provider Bridges (802.1ad) and Provider Backbone Bridges (802.1ah).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] These standards allow for Ethernet networks of planetary scale.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Associated standards (IEEE 802.1ag, and related ITU-T standard Y.1731) provide Operations and Maintenance (OAM) capabilities allowing connectivity verification, rapid recovery, and performance measurement.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3 Working Group in close cooperation with the ITU have been working to simplify the transport of 40G and 100G technologies being developed by both bodies: 802.3 for LAN and ITU for the OTN.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The OIF and the Ethernet Alliance have also been working cooperatively with their members to enable future enhancements to Ethernet for the WAN while looking to the future speed of Ethernet technologies and services.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In serial communication, clock synchronization can refer to clock recovery, which achieves frequency synchronization, as opposed to full phase synchronization.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Such clock synchronization is used in synchronization in telecommunications and automatic baud rate detection.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Plesiochronous or isochronous operation refers to a system with frequency synchronization and loose constraints on phase synchronization.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Synchronous operation implies a tighter synchronization based on time perhaps in addition to frequency.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] As a result of the difficulties managing time at smaller scales, there are problems associated with clock skew that take on more complexity in distributed computing in which several computers will need to realize the same global time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] For instance, in Unix systems, the *make* command is used to compile new or modified code and seeks to avoid recompiling unchanged code.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The *make* command uses the clock of the machine it runs on to determine which source files need to be recompiled.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] If the sources reside on a separate file server and the two machines have unsynchronized clocks, the *make* program might not produce the correct results.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is required for accurate reproduction of streaming media.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Clock synchronization is a significant component of audio over Ethernet systems.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In a system with a central server, the synchronization solution is trivial; the server will dictate the system time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm and the Berkeley algorithm are potential solutions to the clock synchronization problem in this environment.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In distributed computing, the problem takes on more complexity because a global time is not easily known.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The most used clock synchronization solution on the Internet is the Network Time Protocol (NTP), which is a layered client-server architecture based on User Datagram Protocol (UDP) message passing.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Lamport timestamps and vector clocks are concepts of the logical clock in distributed computing.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In a wireless network, the problem becomes even more challenging due to the possibility of collision of the synchronization packets on the wireless medium and the higher drift rate of clocks on low-cost wireless devices.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The Berkeley algorithm is suitable for systems where a radio clock is not present.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] This system has no way of making sure of the actual time other than by maintaining a global average time as the global time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] A time server will periodically fetch the time from all the time clients, average the results, and then report back to the clients the adjustment that needs be made to their local clocks to achieve the average.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] This algorithm highlights the fact that internal clocks may vary not only in the time they contain but also in the clock rate.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Clock-sampling mutual network synchronization (CS-MNS) is suitable for distributed and mobile applications.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] It has been shown to be scalable over mesh networks that include indirectly-linked non-adjacent nodes and is compatible with IEEE 802.11 and similar standards.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] It can be accurate to the order of a few microseconds but requires direct physical wireless connectivity with negligible link delay (less than 1 microsecond) on links between adjacent nodes, limiting the distance between neighboring nodes to a few hundred meters.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm relies on the existence of a time server.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The time server maintains its clock by using a radio clock or other accurate time source, then all other computers in the system stay synchronized with it.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] A time client will maintain its clock by making a procedure call to the time server.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Variations of this algorithm make more precise time calculations by factoring in network radio propagation time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In addition to its use in navigation, the Global Positioning System (GPS) can also be used for clock synchronization.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The accuracy of GPS time signals is ±10 nanoseconds.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Using GPS (or other satellite navigation systems) for synchronization requires a receiver connected to an antenna with unobstructed view of the sky.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] IRIG timecodes are standard formats for transferring timing information.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Atomic frequency standards and GPS receivers designed for precision timing are often equipped with an IRIG output.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The standards were created by the Telecommunications Working Group of the United States military's Inter-Range Instrumentation Group (IRIG), the standards body of the Range Commanders Council.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Work on these standards started in October 1956, and the original standards were accepted in 1960.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Network Time Protocol (NTP) is a highly robust protocol, widely deployed throughout the Internet.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Well tested over the years, it is generally regarded as the state of the art in distributed time synchronization protocols for unreliable networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] It can reduce synchronization offsets to times of the order of a few milliseconds over the public Internet and to sub-millisecond levels over local area networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] A simplified version of the NTP protocol, Simple Network Time Protocol (SNTP), can also be used as a pure single-shot stateless primary/secondary synchronization protocol, but lacks the sophisticated features of NTP, and thus has much lower performance and reliability levels.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Precision Time Protocol (PTP) is a master/slave protocol for delivery of highly accurate time over local area networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Time Synchronization (RBS) algorithm is often used in wireless networks and sensor networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] In this scheme, an initiator broadcasts a reference message to urge the receivers to adjust their clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Infrastructure Synchronization (RBIS) protocol is a master/slave synchronization protocol, like RBS, based on a receiver/receiver synchronization paradigm.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] It is specifically tailored to be used in IEEE 802.11 wireless networks configured in infrastructure mode (i.e., coordinated by an access point).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The protocol does not require any modification to the access point.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Synchronous Ethernet uses Ethernet in a synchronous manner such that when combined with synchronization protocols such as PTP in the case of the White Rabbit Project, sub-nanosecond synchronization accuracy is achieved.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is achieved in wireless ad hoc networks through sending synchronization messages in a multi-hop manner and each node progressively synchronizing with the node that is the immediate sender of a synchronization message.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Examples include Flooding Time Synchronization Protocol (FTSP), and Harmonia, both able to achieve synchronization with accuracy on the order of microseconds.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Researchers from Stanford and Google introduced Huygens, a probe-based, end-to-end clock synchronization algorithm.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] Huygens is implemented in software and thus can be deployed in data centers or in public cloud environments.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] By leveraging some key aspects of modern data centers and applying novel estimation algorithms and signal processing techniques, the Huygens algorithm achieved an accuracy of tens of nanoseconds even at high network load.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/clock-synchronization] The findings of this research are being tested in financial market applications.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The **Precision Time Protocol** (**PTP**) is a protocol for clock synchronization throughout a computer network with relatively high precision as compared to using the earlier developed Network Time Protocol (NTP) and therefore *potentially* higher accuracy depending on the configuration.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] In a local area network (LAN), accuracy can be sub-microsecond – making it suitable for measurement and control systems applications.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2008**, also known as PTP Version 2, is not backward compatible with the 2002 version.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2019** was published in November 2019 and includes backward-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 includes a *profile* concept defining PTP operating parameters and options.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Several profiles have been defined for applications including telecommunications, electric power distribution and audiovisual uses.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 802.1AS** is an adaptation of PTP, called gPTP, for use with Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] According to John Eidson, who led the IEEE 1588-2002 standardization effort, "IEEE 1588 is designed to fill a niche not well served by either of the two dominant protocols, NTP and GPS.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588 is designed for local systems requiring accuracies beyond those attainable using NTP.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] PTP was originally defined in the IEEE 1588-2002 standard, officially titled *Standard for a Precision Clock Synchronization Protocol for Networked Measurement and Control Systems*, and published in 2002.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] In 2008, IEEE 1588-2008 was released as a revised standard; also known as PTP version 2 (PTPv2), it improves accuracy, precision and robustness but is not backward compatible with the original 2002 version.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2019 was published in November 2019, is informally known as *PTPv2.1* and includes backwards-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The IEEE 1588 standards describe a hierarchical master–slave architecture for clock distribution consisting of one or more network segments and one or more clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] An *ordinary clock* is a device with a single network connection that is either the source of or the destination for a synchronization reference.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A source is called a *master* (alternately *timeTransmitter*), and a destination is called a *slave* (alternately *timeReceiver*).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A *boundary clock* has multiple network connections and synchronizes one network segment to another.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A single, synchronization leader is selected, a.k.a. elected, for each network segment.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The root timing reference is called the *grandmaster*.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A relatively simple PTP architecture consists of ordinary clocks on a single-segment network with no boundary clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A grandmaster is elected and all other clocks synchronize to it.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 introduces a clock associated with network equipment used to convey PTP messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The *transparent clock* modifies PTP messages as they pass through the device.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Timestamps in the messages are corrected for time spent traversing the network equipment.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] This scheme improves distribution accuracy by compensating for delivery variability across the network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] PTP typically uses the same epoch as Unix time (start of 1 January 1970).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] While the Unix time is based on Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and is subject to leap seconds, PTP is based on International Atomic Time (TAI).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The PTP grandmaster communicates the current offset between UTC and TAI, so that UTC can be computed from the received PTP time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Synchronization and management of a PTP system is achieved through the exchange of messages across the communications medium.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] To this end, PTP uses the following message types.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Messages are categorized as *event* and *general* messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] *Event* messages are time-critical in that accuracy in transmission and receipt timestamp accuracy directly affects clock distribution accuracy.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] *Sync*, *Delay_Req*, *Pdelay_Req* and *Pdelay_resp* are *event* messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages are more conventional protocol data units in that the data in these messages is of importance to PTP, but their transmission and receipt timestamps are not.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] *Announce*, *Follow_Up*, *Delay_Resp*, *Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up*, *Management* and *Signaling* messages are members of the *general* message class.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] PTP messages may use the User Datagram Protocol over Internet Protocol (UDP/IP) for transport.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses only IPv4 transports, but this has been extended to include IPv6 in IEEE 1588-2008.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2002, all PTP messages are sent using multicast messaging, while IEEE 1588-2008 introduced an option for devices to negotiate unicast transmission on a port-by-port basis.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Multicast transmissions use IP multicast addressing, for which multicast group addresses are defined for IPv4 and IPv6 (see table).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Time-critical *event* messages (Sync, Delay_req, Pdelay_Req and Pdelay_Resp) are sent to port number 319.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages (Announce, Follow_Up, Delay_Resp, Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up, management and signaling) use port number 320.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2008, encapsulation is also defined for DeviceNet, ControlNet and PROFINET.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A domain is an interacting set of clocks that synchronize to one another using PTP.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Clocks are assigned to a domain by virtue of the contents of the *Subdomain name* (IEEE 1588-2002) or the *domainNumber* (IEEE 1588-2008) fields in PTP messages they receive or generate.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Domains allow multiple clock distribution systems to share the same communications medium.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Class – each clock is a member of a given class, each class getting its own priority.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Priority 2 – final-defined priority, defining backup order in case the other criteria were not sufficient.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Smaller numeric values indicate higher priority.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Unique identifier – MAC address-based selection is used as a tiebreaker when all other properties are equal.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses a selection algorithm based on similar properties.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Clock properties are advertised in IEEE 1588-2002 *Sync* messages and in IEEE 1588-2008 *Announce* messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The current leader transmits this information at regular interval.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A clock that considers itself a better leader will transmit this information in order to invoke a change of leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Once the current leader recognizes the better clock, the current leader stops transmitting *Sync* messages and associated clock properties (*Announce* messages in the case of IEEE 1588-2008) and the better clock takes over as leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The BMCA only considers the self-declared quality of clocks and does not take network link quality into consideration.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Via BMCA, PTP selects a source of time for an IEEE 1588 domain and for each network segment in the domain.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Clocks determine the offset between themselves and their leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Let the variable t represent physical time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] where $s(t)$ represents the time measured by the follower clock at physical time t , and $m(t)$ represents the time measured by the leader clock at physical time t .
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The leader periodically broadcasts the current time as a message to the other clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2002 broadcasts are up to once per second.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2008, up to 10 per second are permitted.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Each broadcast begins at time $T_{1}$ with a *Sync* message sent by the leader to all the clocks in the domain.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] A clock receiving this message takes note of the local time $T_{1}'$ when this message is received.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The leader may subsequently send a multicast *Follow_Up* with accurate $T_{1}$ timestamp.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Not all leaders have the ability to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] It is only after the transmission is complete that they are able to retrieve an accurate timestamp for the *Sync* transmission from their network hardware.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with this limitation use the *Follow_Up* message to convey $T_{1}$ .
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with PTP capabilities built into their network hardware are able to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message and do not need to send Follow_Up messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] In order to accurately synchronize to their leader, clocks must individually determine the network transit time of the *Sync* messages.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The transit time is determined indirectly by measuring round-trip time from each clock to its leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The clocks initiate an exchange with their leader designed to measure the transit time d .
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The exchange begins with a clock sending a *Delay_Req* message at time $T_{2}$ to the leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The leader receives and timestamps the *Delay_Req* at time $T_{2}'$ and responds with a *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The leader includes the timestamp $T_{2}'$ in the *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The clock now knows the offset ${\tilde {o}}$ during this transaction and can correct itself by this amount to bring it into agreement with their leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] One assumption is that this exchange of messages happens over a period of time so small that this offset can safely be considered constant over that period.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Another assumption is that the transit time of a message going from the leader to a follower is equal to the transit time of a message going from the follower to the leader.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] Finally, it is assumed that both the leader and follower can accurately measure the time they send or receive a message.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/precision-time-protocol] The degree to which these assumptions hold true determines the accuracy of the clock at the follower device.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] A **master clock** is a precision clock that provides timing signals to synchronise slave clocks as part of a clock network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Networks of electric clocks connected by wires to a precision master pendulum clock began to be used in institutions like factories, offices, and schools around 1900.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Modern radio clocks are synchronised by radio signals or Internet connections to a worldwide time system called Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), which is governed by **primary reference** atomic clocks in many countries.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] A modern, atomic version of a master clock is the large clock ensemble found at the U.S.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Between the late 1800s and the availability of Internet time services, many large institutions that depended on accurate timekeeping such as schools, offices, railway networks, telephone exchanges, and factories used master/slave clock networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] These consisted of multiple slave clocks and other timing devices, connected through wires to a master clock which kept them synchronized by electrical signals.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] The master clock was usually a precision pendulum clock with a seconds pendulum and a robust mechanism.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] It generated periodic timing signals by electrical contacts attached to the mechanism, transmitted to the controlled equipment through pairs of wires.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] The controlled devices could be wall clocks, tower clocks, factory sirens, school bells, time card punches, and paper tape programmers that ran factory machines.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Thousands of such systems were installed in industrial countries and enabled the precise scheduling that industrial economies depended on.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] In early networks, the slave clocks had their own timekeeping mechanism and were just corrected by the signals from the master clock every hour, 6, 12, or 24 hours.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] In later networks, the slave clocks were simply counters that used a stepper motor to advance the hands with each pulse from the master clock, once per second or once per minute.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Some types, such as the Synchronome, had optional extra mechanisms to compare the time of the clock with a national time service that distributed time signals from astronomical regulator clocks in a country's naval observatory by telegraph wire.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] An example is the GPO time service in Britain which distributed signals from the Greenwich Observatory.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] The UK had four such manufacturers, all of whom made clocks to the same GPO specification and which used the Hipp Toggle impulse system; these were Gent and Co., of Leicester, Magneta Ltd of Leatherhead in Surrey, Synchronome Ltd of Alperton, north-west London, and Gillett and Johnson.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Diagram of electric time system used around 1910 to keep time in factories, schools, and other large institutions.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] In addition to wall clocks, it also controls time stamps that are used to stamp documents with the time and a turret clock used in a clock tower.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] is a timer that can be programmed with punched paper tape to ring bells or turn machines on and off at preprogrammed times.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] GPO Master clock type 36 Mark 3, by Gent and Co., UK.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] This clock was made with a synchronising mechanism, responsive to an external signal relayed by land line from the GPO Chronopher at St.Martin's le grand, which in turn, received it from the Greenwich Observatory.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Master clock from synchronised school clock system, c.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/primary-reference-clock] Electromechanical movement winds each minute, and impulses slave clocks each minute.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The aim of Synchronous Ethernet is to provide a synchronization signal to those network resources that may eventually require such a type of signal.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The Synchronous Ethernet signal transmitted over the Ethernet physical layer should be traceable to an external clock, ideally a master and unique clock for the whole network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Applications include cellular networks, access technologies such as Ethernet passive optical network, and applications such as IPTV or VoIP.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Unlike time-division multiplexing networks, the Ethernet family of computer networks do not carry clock synchronization information.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Several means are defined to address this issue.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] IETF’s Network Time Protocol, IEEE's 1588-2008 Precision Time Protocol are some of them.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE architecture minimally requires replacement of the internal clock of the Ethernet card by a phase locked loop in order to feed the Ethernet PHY.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Extension of the synchronization network to consider Ethernet as a building block (ITU-T G.8261).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] This enables Synchronous Ethernet network equipment to be connected to the same synchronization network as Synchronous Digital Hierarchy (SDH).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronization for SDH can be transported over Ethernet and vice-versa.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] ITU-T G.8262 defines Synchronous Ethernet clocks compatible with SDH clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronous Ethernet clocks, based on ITU-T G.813 clocks, are defined in terms of accuracy, noise transfer, holdover performance, noise tolerance and noise generation.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] These clocks are referred as Ethernet Equipment Slave clocks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] While the IEEE 802.3 standard specifies Ethernet clocks to be within ±100 ppm.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] In addition, by timing the Ethernet clock, it is possible to achieve Primary Reference Clock (PRC) traceability at the interfaces.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] G.8262/Y.1362 is an ITU-T recommendation for Synchronous Ethernet that defines "timing characteristics of synchronous Ethernet equipment slave clock (EEC).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] " It was first published in August 2007, amended in 2008 and 2010 and a new version published in 2010.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the Synchronization Status Message (SSM) provides traceability of synchronization signals and it is therefore required to extend the SSM functionality to Synchronous Ethernet to achieve full interoperability with SDH equipment.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the SSM message is carried in fixed locations within the SDH frame.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] However, in Ethernet there is no equivalent of a fixed frame.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The mechanisms needed to transport the SSM over Synchronous Ethernet are defined by the ITU-T in G.8264 in cooperation with IEEE.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] More specifically, the ESMC, defined by the ITU-T is based on the Organization Specific Slow Protocol (OSSP), currently specified in IEEE 802.3ay.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The ITU-T G.8264 defines a background or heart-beat message to provide a continuous indication of the clock quality level.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] However, event type messages with a new SSM quality level are generated immediately.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The ESMC protocol is composed of the standard Ethernet header for a slow protocol, an ITU-T specific header, a flag field and a type length value (TLV) structure.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The SSM encoded within the TLV is a four-bit field whose meaning is described in ITU-T G.781.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] A general requirement for SyncE was that any network element (NE) should have at least two reference clocks, and in addition, Ethernet interfaces must be able to generate their own synchronization signal in case they lose their external reference.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] If such is the case, it is said that the Ethernet node (EN) is in holdover.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronous signal must be filtered and regenerated by phase locked loop (PLL) at the Ethernet nodes since it degrades when passing through the network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronization and transport networks are partially mixed, since some NEs both transmit data and distribute clock signals to other NEs.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE networks do not usually have only one topology, but rather a combination of all of them.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Duplication and security involving more than one master clock, and the existence of some kind of synchronization management protocol, are important features of modern networks.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] The aim is to minimize the problems associated with signal transport, and to avoid depending on only one clock in case of failure.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] As a result, we get an extremely precise, redundant, and solid synchronization network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Several type of networks can be used to transport the synchronous signal and could be combined indeed.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] Some of these networks are T1/E1, SONET/SDH and any rate, and SyncE.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] However *legacy Ethernet* is not suitable for transmitting synchronization signals.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] This is important because if the signal crosses a legacy Ethernet island then the synchronization is lost.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] *Line timing*: The NE obtains its clock by deriving it from one of the input signals.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] *Through timing*: Where the Tx outputs of one interface are synchronized with the Rx inputs of the opposite interface.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] *Internal timing*: In this mode, the internal clock of the EEC is used to synchronize outputs.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] It may be a temporary holdover stage after losing the synchronization signal, or it may be a simple line configuration where no other clock is available.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] A timing loop is in bad synchronization when the clock signal has closed itself, but there is no clock, either master or slave, that would autonomously generate a non-deficient clock signal.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] This situation can be caused by a fault affecting an NE in such a way that it has been left without a reference clock, and therefore it has chosen an alternative synchronization: a signal that has turned out to be the same signal, returning by another route.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/synchronous-ethernet] A synchronization loop is a completely unstable situation that may provoke an immediate collapse of part of the network within the loop.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is a type of time-division multiplexing (TDM), with the special point that instead of having one transmitter connected to one receiver, there are multiple transmitters.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is used in digital 2G cellular systems such as Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM), IS-136, Personal Digital Cellular (PDC) and iDEN, in the Maritime Automatic Identification System, and in the Digital Enhanced Cordless Telecommunications (DECT) standard for portable phones.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA was first used in satellite communication systems by Western Union in its Westar 3 communications satellite in 1979.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] It is now used extensively in satellite communications, combat-net radio systems, and passive optical network (PON) networks for upstream traffic from premises to the operator.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Most 2G cellular systems, with the notable exception of IS-95, are based on TDMA.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] GSM, D-AMPS, PDC, iDEN, and PHS are all examples of TDMA cellular systems.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In the GSM system, the synchronization of the mobile phones is achieved by sending timing advance commands from the base station, which instruct the mobile phone to transmit earlier and by how much.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This compensates for the speed-of-light propagation delay between phone and base station.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile phone is not allowed to transmit for its entire time slot; there is a guard interval at the end of each time slot.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] As the transmission moves into the guard period, the mobile network updates the timing advance to synchronize the transmission.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Initial synchronization of a phone requires a special procedure.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Before a mobile transmits, there is no way to know the timing advance required.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] For this reason, an entire time slot is dedicated to mobiles attempting to contact the network; this is known as the random-access channel (RACH) in GSM.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile transmits at the beginning of the time slot as received from the network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] If the mobile is near the base station, the propagation delay is short and the initiation can succeed.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] If, however, the mobile phone is farther than 35 km from the base station, the delay will mean the mobile's transmission arrives at the end of the time slot.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In this case, the mobile will be instructed to transmit its messages starting nearly a whole time slot earlier so that it can be received at the proper time.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Finally, if the mobile is beyond the 35 km cell range of GSM, the transmission will arrive in a neighbouring time slot and be ignored.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] It is this feature, rather than limitations of power, that limits the range of a GSM cell to 35 km when no special extension techniques are used.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] By changing the synchronization between the uplink and downlink at the base station, however, this limitation can be overcome.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-FDD (frequency division duplex) employs CDMA and FDD, where separate frequency bands are allocated for uplink and downlink transmissions.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This separation minimizes interference and allows for continuous data transmission in both directions, making it suitable for environments with balanced traffic loads.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-TDD (time division duplex), on the other hand, combines CDMA with TDMA and TDD.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In this scheme, the same frequency band is used for both uplink and downlink, but at different times.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This time-based separation is particularly advantageous in scenarios with asymmetric traffic loads, where the data rates for uplink and downlink differ significantly.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] By dynamically allocating time slots based on demand, UTRA-TDD can efficiently manage varying traffic patterns and enhance overall network capacity.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] The combination of these technologies in UMTS allows for more flexible and efficient use of the available spectrum, catering to diverse user demands and improving the adaptability of 3G networks to different operational environments.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] The ITU-T G.hn standard, which provides high-speed local area networking over existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables) is based on a TDMA scheme.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In G.hn, a *master* device allocates *contention-free transmission opportunities* (CFTXOP) to other *slave* devices in the network.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Only one device can use a CFTXOP at a time, thus avoiding collisions.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] FlexRay protocol, which is also a wired network used for safety-critical communication in modern cars, uses the TDMA method for data transmission control.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In radio systems, TDMA is usually used alongside frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) and frequency-division duplex (FDD); the combination is referred to as FDMA/TDMA/FDD.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This is the case in both GSM and IS-136, for example.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Exceptions to this include the DECT and Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) micro-cellular systems, UMTS-TDD UMTS variant, and China's TD-SCDMA, which use time-division duplexing, where different time slots are allocated for the base station and handsets on the same frequency.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] A major advantage of TDMA is that the radio part of the mobile phone only needs to listen and broadcast for its own time slot.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] For the rest of the time, the mobile can carry out measurements on the network, detecting surrounding transmitters on different frequencies.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This allows safe inter-frequency handovers, something which is difficult in CDMA systems, not supported at all in IS-95 and supported through complex system additions in Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS).
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This, in turn, allows for co-existence of microcell layers with macrocell layers.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA, by comparison, supports *soft hand-off*, which allows a mobile phone to be in communication with up to 6 base stations simultaneously, a type of *same-frequency handover*.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] The incoming packets are compared for quality, and the best one is selected.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA's *cell breathing* characteristic, where a terminal on the boundary of two congested cells will be unable to receive a clear signal, can often negate this advantage during peak periods.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] A disadvantage of TDMA systems is that they create interference at a frequency that is directly connected to the time slot length.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This is the buzz that can sometimes be heard if a TDMA phone is left next to a radio or speakers.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Another disadvantage is that the *dead time* between time slots limits the potential bandwidth of a TDMA channel.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] These are implemented in part because of the difficulty in ensuring that different terminals transmit at exactly the times required.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] Handsets that are moving will need to constantly adjust their timings to ensure their transmission is received at precisely the right time, because as they move further from the base station, their signal will take longer to arrive.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] This also means that the major TDMA systems have hard limits on cell sizes in terms of range, though in practice, the power levels required to receive and transmit over distances greater than the supported range would be mostly impractical anyway.
[src:synchronous-ethernet/time-division-multiple-access] In **dynamic time-division multiple access** (**dynamic TDMA**), a scheduling algorithm dynamically reserves a variable number of time slots in each frame to variable bit-rate data streams, based on the traffic demand of each data stream.
